.TH "DATE.SETSECONDS" "3JS" "July 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Date.setSeconds \- Date.prototype.setSeconds()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]setSeconds()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]Date\f[R]
instances changes the seconds and/or milliseconds for this date
according to local time.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] event = \f[B]new\f[R] Date(\(dqAugust 19, 1975 23:15:30\(dq);

event.setSeconds(42);

console.log(event.getSeconds());
\f[I]// Expected output: 42\f[R]

console.log(event);
\f[I]// Expected output: \(dqSat Apr 19 1975 23:15:42 GMT+0100 (CET)\(dq\f[R]
\f[I]// Note: your timezone may vary\f[R]
.EE
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
setSeconds(secondsValue)
setSeconds(secondsValue, msValue)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]secondsValue\f[R]
An integer between 0 and 59 representing the seconds.
.TP
\f[B]msValue\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An integer between 0 and 999 representing the milliseconds.
.SS Return value
Changes the \f[CR]Date\f[R] object in place, and returns its new
timestamp.
If a parameter is \f[CR]NaN\f[R] (or other values that get coerced to
\f[CR]NaN\f[R], such as \f[CR]undefined\f[R]), the date is set to
Invalid Date and \f[CR]NaN\f[R] is returned.
.SH DESCRIPTION
If you do not specify the \f[CR]msValue\f[R] parameter, the value
returned from the \f[CR]getMilliseconds()\f[R] method is used.
.PP
If a parameter you specify is outside of the expected range,
\f[CR]setSeconds()\f[R] attempts to update the date information in the
\f[CR]Date\f[R] object accordingly.
For example, if you use 100 for \f[CR]secondsValue\f[R], the minutes
stored in the \f[CR]Date\f[R] object will be incremented by 1, and 40
will be used for seconds.
.PP
Because \f[CR]setSeconds()\f[R] operates on the local time, crossing a
Daylight Saving Time (DST) boundary may result in a different elapsed
time than expected.
For example, if setting the seconds crosses a spring\-forward transition
(losing an hour), the difference in timestamps between the new and old
date is one hour less than the nominal time difference.
Conversely, crossing a fall\-back transition (gaining an hour) result in
an extra hour.
If you need to adjust the date by a fixed amount of time, consider using
\f[CR]setUTCSeconds()\f[R] or \f[CR]setTime()\f[R].
.PP
If the new local time falls within an offset transition, the exact time
is derived using the same behavior as \f[CR]Temporal\f[R]\(cqs
\f[CR]disambiguation: \(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R] option.
That is, if the local time corresponds to two instants, the earlier one
is chosen; if the local time does not exist (there is a gap), we go
forward by the gap duration.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using setSeconds()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] theBigDay = \f[B]new\f[R] Date();
theBigDay.setSeconds(30);
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Date.prototype.getSeconds()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Date.prototype.setUTCSeconds()\f[R]
